00:00:28.945 --> 00:00:30.960
JULIAN BEINART: The
next three classes

00:00:30.960 --> 00:00:36.270
deal with a discussion of three
models, which we developed

00:00:36.270 --> 00:00:43.020
in this class with Kevin
Lynch, and I've subsequently

00:00:43.020 --> 00:00:46.260
changed and added to.

00:00:46.260 --> 00:00:49.200
The three models are not unique.

00:00:49.200 --> 00:00:52.620
They are examples
of models which

00:00:52.620 --> 00:00:57.740
inform the form of the
city, have instructions

00:00:57.740 --> 00:01:05.880
as who should take part,
have premises of materialism

00:01:05.880 --> 00:01:09.180
or theism associated with them.

00:01:12.560 --> 00:01:15.780
I'll go through the
first one today,

00:01:15.780 --> 00:01:19.450
what we call the cosmic model.

00:01:19.450 --> 00:01:26.100
And you can see that the
definitions of states

00:01:26.100 --> 00:01:35.730
is subjective, control
science, nature, type, and form

00:01:35.730 --> 00:01:40.365
tools will be what we will
discuss in this class.

00:01:44.930 --> 00:01:50.390
The most common
theory associated

00:01:50.390 --> 00:01:56.870
with the beginning of cities
has a materialist basis.

00:01:56.870 --> 00:02:00.170
This is of course wrong.

00:02:00.170 --> 00:02:06.020
The materialist basis
is based on the notion

00:02:06.020 --> 00:02:09.590
that a surplus is produced
through agriculture.

00:02:09.590 --> 00:02:16.190
And a surplus requires a system
of bureaucracy, a literature,

00:02:16.190 --> 00:02:24.260
or literal elite, a method for
controlling irrigation systems,

00:02:24.260 --> 00:02:27.380
and so on, and the
primitive notions of trade.

00:02:31.640 --> 00:02:35.000
Why don't I just read you
a standard explanation

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:39.140
of surplus, because you
should remember the word.

00:02:39.140 --> 00:02:42.320
It's an important
word in the theory

00:02:42.320 --> 00:02:46.700
of city form, the notion
of the production of more

00:02:46.700 --> 00:02:48.470
than you need.

00:02:48.470 --> 00:02:52.700
It involves storage, it
involves the world of--

00:02:52.700 --> 00:02:57.680
that's why I regard the
invention of the potter's wheel

00:02:57.680 --> 00:03:03.470
is one of the more significant
inventions of humankind.

00:03:03.470 --> 00:03:04.670
How do you store food?

00:03:09.810 --> 00:03:11.610
What do you do with
the surplus of food

00:03:11.610 --> 00:03:14.070
unless you have commodities
or containers that

00:03:14.070 --> 00:03:19.155
can separate the food from the
corrosion forces of nature--

00:03:21.810 --> 00:03:22.395
the surplus.

00:03:28.900 --> 00:03:31.750
"Surplus production
beyond the immediate needs

00:03:31.750 --> 00:03:35.950
of the community made possible
the emancipation of some people

00:03:35.950 --> 00:03:38.470
from the toils of the land."

00:03:38.470 --> 00:03:43.270
Here's an interesting
observation--

00:03:43.270 --> 00:03:48.040
that if you produce excess,
you relieve certain people

00:03:48.040 --> 00:03:51.550
of conventional duties.

00:03:51.550 --> 00:03:54.790
We have excess
which relieves a man

00:03:54.790 --> 00:03:58.120
to become the conductor of
the New York Philharmonic

00:03:58.120 --> 00:03:59.890
Orchestra.

00:03:59.890 --> 00:04:05.920
It's only when you
have a surplus which

00:04:05.920 --> 00:04:11.050
is not taken into account in
much of our modern economics.

00:04:11.050 --> 00:04:14.230
"But this creates
the opportunity

00:04:14.230 --> 00:04:16.060
for specialized
source and groups

00:04:16.060 --> 00:04:21.490
associated with namely scribes,
craftsmen, priests, warriors.

00:04:21.490 --> 00:04:24.190
Surplus production
presumes irrigation

00:04:24.190 --> 00:04:28.600
and efficient irrigation system
produces a complex bureaucracy.

00:04:28.600 --> 00:04:31.390
And that means cities."

00:04:31.390 --> 00:04:38.290
This theory, materialist
theory, is best written

00:04:38.290 --> 00:04:42.580
about in Gideon Sjoberg's
book, The Preindustrial City--

00:04:42.580 --> 00:04:49.330
S-J-O-B-E-R-G-- and in Gordon
Child, an Australian writer,

00:04:49.330 --> 00:04:52.370
who wrote a book called
Man Makes Himself.

00:04:52.370 --> 00:04:55.360
These are classic depictions
of surplus theory.

00:04:58.440 --> 00:05:01.060
There's a version of
surplus subdivision,

00:05:01.060 --> 00:05:04.730
of surplus theory
into two kinds.

00:05:04.730 --> 00:05:08.140
One held by Jane
Jacobs in her book

00:05:08.140 --> 00:05:11.620
The Economy of Cities,
which argues that

00:05:11.620 --> 00:05:14.530
in the town of Catalhuyuk--

00:05:14.530 --> 00:05:21.100
C-A-T-A-L-H-U-Y-U-K, was
the center for industrial

00:05:21.100 --> 00:05:23.410
production of obsidian.

00:05:23.410 --> 00:05:27.040
And agricultural served,
as it does conventionally

00:05:27.040 --> 00:05:33.250
in our societies, as
the source of production

00:05:33.250 --> 00:05:38.380
for industrial commodities
such as obsidian.

00:05:38.380 --> 00:05:42.460
This is different from the
agricultural surplus, which

00:05:42.460 --> 00:05:45.610
regards agriculture as
the primary function

00:05:45.610 --> 00:05:49.390
and pays no attention
to material production.

00:05:54.900 --> 00:05:58.740
Most students of
the origin of cities

00:05:58.740 --> 00:06:02.380
now don't believe in either
of these two propositions.

00:06:02.380 --> 00:06:04.530
So forget them.

00:06:04.530 --> 00:06:07.670
They're not important.

00:06:07.670 --> 00:06:15.530
The common version
of this new theory

00:06:15.530 --> 00:06:21.950
suggests that original cities
were ceremonial centers, places

00:06:21.950 --> 00:06:26.300
of holy ritual, which explains
the risky force of nature

00:06:26.300 --> 00:06:29.340
and secured them
for human benefit.

00:06:29.340 --> 00:06:31.520
Peasants supported
them voluntarily,

00:06:31.520 --> 00:06:34.020
attracted by their
holy power, thus

00:06:34.020 --> 00:06:41.420
arose a permanent priestly
class, awesome and seductive.

00:06:41.420 --> 00:06:45.290
Only later did the marks of
urban civilization appear--

00:06:45.290 --> 00:06:49.970
ore, trade, writing, extensive
cross-specialization, and so

00:06:49.970 --> 00:06:51.090
on.

00:06:51.090 --> 00:06:54.230
So that the first cities
were mental weapons, not

00:06:54.230 --> 00:06:57.290
physical forces.

00:06:57.290 --> 00:07:04.510
Now, let's look at some of
this a bit more carefully.

00:07:11.290 --> 00:07:17.590
Joseph Rykwert in a book called
The Idea of a Town writing

00:07:17.590 --> 00:07:22.390
about the definition
of Roman cities--

00:07:22.390 --> 00:07:27.390
"the Romans are considered
to be the prime rationalists

00:07:27.390 --> 00:07:32.680
of ancient times and
the towns are often

00:07:32.680 --> 00:07:37.570
seen as rational outcomes
of surveying technique

00:07:37.570 --> 00:07:46.370
and military fortification.

00:07:46.370 --> 00:07:50.390
I quote, Rykwert says,
"the town is not really

00:07:50.390 --> 00:07:53.810
a natural phenomenon,"
here setting up

00:07:53.810 --> 00:08:00.140
a distinction between the
form of the town and nature.

00:08:00.140 --> 00:08:03.230
We'll get into the
fallacies of biomorphosis

00:08:03.230 --> 00:08:05.780
and so on as we go
through this class.

00:08:05.780 --> 00:08:09.440
You will understand that
I'm not a naturalist.

00:08:09.440 --> 00:08:14.330
I understand that everything
that happens around us

00:08:14.330 --> 00:08:18.020
is processed by the
amount of material,

00:08:18.020 --> 00:08:22.190
the 1,250 cubic centimeters
in the human brain.

00:08:25.150 --> 00:08:30.190
It's interesting in talking
about the cosmic model

00:08:30.190 --> 00:08:35.169
to notice the definition
in formal religion

00:08:35.169 --> 00:08:37.610
of the idea of heaven.

00:08:37.610 --> 00:08:40.200
Heaven is only a
concept of humankind.

00:08:43.720 --> 00:08:45.515
We'll touch on that a bit later.

00:08:50.560 --> 00:08:55.925
Lewis Mumford-- just choosing
little bits from these

00:08:55.925 --> 00:08:56.425
sources--

00:09:00.010 --> 00:09:02.740
"the original aspects
of temporary settlements

00:09:02.740 --> 00:09:05.440
have to do with sacred
things, not just

00:09:05.440 --> 00:09:07.720
with the physical environment.

00:09:07.720 --> 00:09:12.250
They relate to a more valuable
and meaningful kind of life

00:09:12.250 --> 00:09:17.260
where a consciousness that
entertains past and future

00:09:17.260 --> 00:09:20.920
apprehensive primal mysteries
of sexual generation

00:09:20.920 --> 00:09:23.050
and the ultimate
mystery of death

00:09:23.050 --> 00:09:25.720
and what may lie beyond death.

00:09:25.720 --> 00:09:29.140
These central concerns
about is the very reason

00:09:29.140 --> 00:09:32.110
for the city's
existence, inseparable

00:09:32.110 --> 00:09:37.960
from the economic substance
that makes it possible."

00:09:37.960 --> 00:09:43.240
Another item from
Mumford talking

00:09:43.240 --> 00:09:48.190
about the exaggerated
height and thickness

00:09:48.190 --> 00:09:51.760
of walls in earlier cities.

00:09:51.760 --> 00:09:56.410
The wall of Khorsabad
which is an Assyrian town,

00:09:56.410 --> 00:10:00.790
the fourth capital city
of the Kingdom of Assyria,

00:10:00.790 --> 00:10:04.330
built around 700 BC--

00:10:04.330 --> 00:10:07.270
the walls are 75 feet thick.

00:10:07.270 --> 00:10:13.840
There is no possibility that
you build 75 feet thick walls

00:10:13.840 --> 00:10:16.380
for military purposes.

00:10:16.380 --> 00:10:20.110
In Mumford's term, it
is only for the gods

00:10:20.110 --> 00:10:24.250
that men exert themselves
so extravagantly.

00:10:24.250 --> 00:10:25.390
It's a wonderful phrase.

00:10:25.390 --> 00:10:27.980
Remember it, never forget it.

00:10:27.980 --> 00:10:31.540
It's only for the
gods that men, if you

00:10:31.540 --> 00:10:34.600
wish to enlarge
the notion of gods,

00:10:34.600 --> 00:10:40.690
and I'll discussed the notion
of a god gene a bit later.

00:10:43.630 --> 00:10:49.000
What we do is not only based on
simple postulates of function.

00:10:52.390 --> 00:11:00.490
It's central to
architecture as a discipline

00:11:00.490 --> 00:11:04.930
that it's only for
gods that men exerts

00:11:04.930 --> 00:11:07.570
themselves so extensively.

00:11:07.570 --> 00:11:13.760
Quoting from another source,
"every feature of the city

00:11:13.760 --> 00:11:18.040
reveals the belief that man was
created for no other purpose

00:11:18.040 --> 00:11:21.190
than to magnify
and serve his gods.

00:11:21.190 --> 00:11:26.738
That was the city's
ultimate reason for being."

00:11:26.738 --> 00:11:30.610
Now here you have
two postulates.

00:11:30.610 --> 00:11:34.960
You have to survive,
you're at the birth

00:11:34.960 --> 00:11:42.550
of an instrument, a city, which
both has to deal with-- so

00:11:42.550 --> 00:11:46.420
your survival possibility.

00:11:46.420 --> 00:11:49.000
You look to the stars.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:52.640
The stars are permanent.

00:11:52.640 --> 00:11:57.280
It's not really difficult
to erect a vertical stick,

00:11:57.280 --> 00:12:01.840
a gnomon, in Mesopotamia.

00:12:01.840 --> 00:12:08.890
And at noon, the stick will
cast a shadow to the north.

00:12:08.890 --> 00:12:13.210
You'll be able to build
a compass around that.

00:12:13.210 --> 00:12:15.170
At the same time
it's doing that,

00:12:15.170 --> 00:12:23.110
you will wonder why the town of
Chang'an in 190 BC in China is

00:12:23.110 --> 00:12:27.400
built according to the
stars of the Dipper.

00:12:27.400 --> 00:12:29.290
I will show you a
slide of that plan.

00:12:29.290 --> 00:12:33.160
It's one of the
remarkable plans.

00:12:33.160 --> 00:12:42.970
So the stability of astronomy
in the earliest cycles of cities

00:12:42.970 --> 00:12:50.110
and the creation of a deity
significance in relation

00:12:50.110 --> 00:12:54.580
to each of these acts, it's one
thing to know where north is.

00:12:54.580 --> 00:12:57.520
It's another thing to
build your city according

00:12:57.520 --> 00:13:02.170
to the primary
objectives of religion.

00:13:02.170 --> 00:13:06.990
We'll go on a little, but
picking up little aspect

00:13:06.990 --> 00:13:07.540
to this.

00:13:12.330 --> 00:13:14.430
Most of the
significant buildings

00:13:14.430 --> 00:13:20.290
built in archaic times
involve enormous amounts

00:13:20.290 --> 00:13:23.200
of human labor.

00:13:23.200 --> 00:13:26.350
For the Pyramid of
Cheops, which has nothing

00:13:26.350 --> 00:13:29.040
to do with function whatsoever.

00:13:29.040 --> 00:13:31.180
It has nothing to
do with materialism.

00:13:31.180 --> 00:13:35.140
It is in fact such an
exhaustion of materialism.

00:13:38.140 --> 00:13:45.400
The Pyramid of Cheops took
100,000 men 20 years to build.

00:13:45.400 --> 00:13:47.830
The Great Pyramid
of Cheops was built

00:13:47.830 --> 00:13:54.310
with about 2,300,000 blocks
of stone, totaling about six

00:13:54.310 --> 00:13:56.410
million tons in weight.

00:13:56.410 --> 00:14:00.550
They have blocks that average
two and 1/2 tons, but range up

00:14:00.550 --> 00:14:04.960
to 15 tons, which
have to be quarried,

00:14:04.960 --> 00:14:09.040
handled, and
transported up a river,

00:14:09.040 --> 00:14:12.280
lifted 100 feet to
the level of the site

00:14:12.280 --> 00:14:16.090
with sledges, rollers,
sleepers, ropes, and levers.

00:14:16.090 --> 00:14:19.780
You don't do that
for anything other

00:14:19.780 --> 00:14:26.035
than the belief in
the post-secular life.

00:14:28.780 --> 00:14:32.620
Egypt didn't produce
any large cities

00:14:32.620 --> 00:14:37.400
for various reasons, which we'll
talk about later in this class.

00:14:37.400 --> 00:14:47.560
But many argue that much of
the disposition of resources

00:14:47.560 --> 00:14:49.720
consequently centered
on the building

00:14:49.720 --> 00:14:55.295
of post-contemporary life.

00:15:02.500 --> 00:15:08.050
The most significant buildings
in most of these early cities

00:15:08.050 --> 00:15:09.885
are religious buildings.

00:15:09.885 --> 00:15:14.080
They're generally built out
of compression structures.

00:15:14.080 --> 00:15:20.140
Solomon's Temple at
1000 BC in Jerusalem,

00:15:20.140 --> 00:15:25.270
Herod's Temple, 70 years
before the birth of Christ--

00:15:25.270 --> 00:15:28.960
both enormous
compression structures.

00:15:28.960 --> 00:15:31.450
Associated with these
compression structures,

00:15:31.450 --> 00:15:34.600
which in generally can't
go up to more than 200

00:15:34.600 --> 00:15:38.690
to 300 feet in height.

00:15:38.690 --> 00:15:43.450
The temples of Chichen Itza in
Mesoamerica-- about 200 feet.

00:15:43.450 --> 00:15:48.230
The Tower of Babel is
about 200 feet in height.

00:15:48.230 --> 00:15:50.680
The Tower of Babel has
the Temple of Marduk

00:15:50.680 --> 00:15:52.720
on the top of the
Tower of Babel.

00:15:55.800 --> 00:15:58.440
All of this is
synchronous with the fact

00:15:58.440 --> 00:16:02.670
that religion was interpreted
not by every person

00:16:02.670 --> 00:16:08.430
but by gurus, by priests, people
who achieved enormous power,

00:16:08.430 --> 00:16:12.750
but didn't distribute the
secrets of their power.

00:16:12.750 --> 00:16:15.870
The Holy of Holies
in Solomon's Temple

00:16:15.870 --> 00:16:21.810
is still being sought for
by filmmakers and people who

00:16:21.810 --> 00:16:25.710
want to excavate under the
Holy Mountain in Jerusalem.

00:16:25.710 --> 00:16:31.485
Of course, something which is
prohibited by political forces.

00:16:34.620 --> 00:16:40.050
The origin of the mosque,
the church, and the synagogue

00:16:40.050 --> 00:16:44.370
is later, in my view.

00:16:44.370 --> 00:16:54.990
The democracy of religion, which
we all know utilized, I think

00:16:54.990 --> 00:16:58.380
comes in a different pattern.

00:16:58.380 --> 00:17:03.860
The first action that I
think in this direction

00:17:03.860 --> 00:17:08.989
comes from the Jewish
exile in 700 BC.

00:17:11.660 --> 00:17:14.240
Nebuchadnezzar and
the Babylonian Army

00:17:14.240 --> 00:17:17.660
destroys the first
Solomon's Temple.

00:17:17.660 --> 00:17:21.200
He takes the Jews
in exile to Babylon.

00:17:21.200 --> 00:17:25.579
Babylon is the greatest city
in the world at the time.

00:17:25.579 --> 00:17:27.950
The Jews don't abandon
their religion,

00:17:27.950 --> 00:17:30.830
despite the fact that
they don't have a temple

00:17:30.830 --> 00:17:34.940
and they don't have priests.

00:17:34.940 --> 00:17:38.900
They start praying
in schools, in homes.

00:17:38.900 --> 00:17:44.150
Ezekiel appears as part of--

00:17:44.150 --> 00:17:46.880
how many chapters of
Ezekiel are in the beginning

00:17:46.880 --> 00:17:49.280
of the Old Testament?

00:17:49.280 --> 00:17:50.540
A whole bunch of them.

00:17:50.540 --> 00:17:52.400
What are they about?

00:17:52.400 --> 00:17:58.040
They are all about
measurements of a temple.

00:17:58.040 --> 00:18:00.140
These measurements
have been interpreted

00:18:00.140 --> 00:18:03.200
in all kinds of ways over time.

00:18:03.200 --> 00:18:07.070
The fact is that when the Jews
were released from Babylon

00:18:07.070 --> 00:18:10.490
in exile, they
returned to Jerusalem

00:18:10.490 --> 00:18:15.270
and Israel read the Bible to
the people for the first time.

00:18:15.270 --> 00:18:18.230
Later on, I think one of
the conflicts about Jesus,

00:18:18.230 --> 00:18:21.560
in my view-- and I will go
into this in more detail

00:18:21.560 --> 00:18:23.120
in the story of Jerusalem--

00:18:27.170 --> 00:18:31.250
is the fact that the synagogue
and the democratic religion

00:18:31.250 --> 00:18:35.270
was growing in power
under the Pharisees

00:18:35.270 --> 00:18:40.760
and that Herod's Temple
was the last resort

00:18:40.760 --> 00:18:43.910
of the power of the priests.

00:18:43.910 --> 00:18:49.250
And Jesus was a
confrontation to the priests,

00:18:49.250 --> 00:18:54.290
to the Jewish priests,
who are on the way out.

00:18:54.290 --> 00:19:04.000
And his death was the mark of
the transition in Christianity

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:08.890
from, well, the birth of
Christianity to the church--

00:19:08.890 --> 00:19:13.990
and later on, 700 years
later, to the mosque.

00:19:13.990 --> 00:19:18.010
So we have an image of
the pre-democratic church

00:19:18.010 --> 00:19:21.700
environment as buildings
of compression,

00:19:21.700 --> 00:19:25.720
no penetration of the
building by the people,

00:19:25.720 --> 00:19:28.600
the slaughtering of animals.

00:19:28.600 --> 00:19:32.020
At Solomon's Temple, I
think 200,000 animals

00:19:32.020 --> 00:19:34.390
were slaughtered, or 20,000.

00:19:34.390 --> 00:19:35.180
It doesn't matter.

00:19:35.180 --> 00:19:36.970
It's just a number.

00:19:39.480 --> 00:19:45.690
The giving a gift at
the birth of a ritual

00:19:45.690 --> 00:19:48.590
is also part of that
same phenomenon.

00:19:51.110 --> 00:19:54.170
Many of these
priestly directions

00:19:54.170 --> 00:19:58.100
still occur in some ways
in contemporary religion.

00:19:58.100 --> 00:20:04.370
Anyway, so we have
an image of a town

00:20:04.370 --> 00:20:09.080
as a pristine object
which changes very

00:20:09.080 --> 00:20:11.570
regularly and under control.

00:20:11.570 --> 00:20:16.190
It doesn't change sporadically,
it stays the same.

00:20:16.190 --> 00:20:20.525
Population growth is very
low, death rates are high.

00:20:23.390 --> 00:20:27.980
Population growth rates in
medieval Europe due to disease

00:20:27.980 --> 00:20:31.320
was something like
0.6% per annum.

00:20:31.320 --> 00:20:35.990
So the idea that things change
very radically and very rapidly

00:20:35.990 --> 00:20:38.210
is a very contemporary idea.

00:20:38.210 --> 00:20:41.510
You could build a city in
which everything roughly was

00:20:41.510 --> 00:20:43.070
the same.

00:20:43.070 --> 00:20:45.920
And the routines for
understanding it and managing

00:20:45.920 --> 00:20:48.860
it are also more
or less the same.

00:20:48.860 --> 00:20:55.460
This kind of city is a
mental force in itself.

00:20:55.460 --> 00:20:59.000
It accumulates the
understanding of it,

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:01.265
it's perpetuated
through rituals.

00:21:03.800 --> 00:21:09.650
Rituals, according to
Mircea Eliade, E-L-I-A-D-E,

00:21:09.650 --> 00:21:15.800
a Romanian religious philosopher
whom I will quote for in a few

00:21:15.800 --> 00:21:20.840
minutes, these
are distinct-- oh,

00:21:20.840 --> 00:21:22.580
let's wait until we get there.

00:21:27.500 --> 00:21:33.440
Human life is thereby given
a secure and permanent place.

00:21:33.440 --> 00:21:36.090
The gods [INAUDIBLE]
is kept often,

00:21:36.090 --> 00:21:39.215
not incidentally, the
structure of human power,

00:21:39.215 --> 00:21:44.600
of priests and kings, and
abilities is also maintained.

00:21:49.410 --> 00:21:58.750
Let's listen to Eliade's
depiction of archaic man.

00:21:58.750 --> 00:22:02.350
"If we observe the general
behavior of archaic man,

00:22:02.350 --> 00:22:05.020
we are struck by
the following fact--

00:22:05.020 --> 00:22:07.570
neither the objects
of the external world

00:22:07.570 --> 00:22:10.420
nor human act,
properly speaking,

00:22:10.420 --> 00:22:13.780
have any autonomous
intrinsic value.

00:22:13.780 --> 00:22:20.880
Objects or acts acquire
the significance

00:22:20.880 --> 00:22:24.270
and become real
because they reenact

00:22:24.270 --> 00:22:29.160
after one fashion or another a
reality that transcends them."

00:22:29.160 --> 00:22:31.650
This is difficult
stuff to understand.

00:22:31.650 --> 00:22:36.510
"Amongst my countless stones,
one stone becomes sacred,

00:22:36.510 --> 00:22:40.410
and then instantly becomes
saturated with being.

00:22:40.410 --> 00:22:44.760
It becomes reality as opposed
to an everyday reality.

00:22:44.760 --> 00:22:51.750
It constitutes a hierophany
H-I-E-R-O-P-H-N-E-Y,

00:22:51.750 --> 00:22:55.900
because it commemorates a
mythical act, and so on.

00:22:55.900 --> 00:22:59.700
The object appears as the
receptacle of an external force

00:22:59.700 --> 00:23:06.920
to differentiate it from
the crude product of nature.

00:23:06.920 --> 00:23:09.620
The object fashioned
by the industry of man

00:23:09.620 --> 00:23:12.560
acquire the reality,
the identity,

00:23:12.560 --> 00:23:16.310
only to the extent of
their participation

00:23:16.310 --> 00:23:20.360
in a transcendent reality."

00:23:20.360 --> 00:23:24.170
In relation to the
form of cities,

00:23:24.170 --> 00:23:28.080
Eliade talks about three things.

00:23:28.080 --> 00:23:30.350
Reality is a function
of the imitation

00:23:30.350 --> 00:23:32.990
of a celestial archetype.

00:23:32.990 --> 00:23:35.300
I mentioned before.

00:23:35.300 --> 00:23:38.250
Number 2, the symbolism
of the center.

00:23:42.970 --> 00:23:46.710
Why a center?

00:23:46.710 --> 00:23:52.410
The word Babylon means the
conjunction of the heaven

00:23:52.410 --> 00:23:55.710
and earth and the subterranean.

00:23:55.710 --> 00:24:01.290
Jerusalem is known for its
being a city on the ground.

00:24:01.290 --> 00:24:07.080
In Christianic terms, there's
a city 15 miles above.

00:24:07.080 --> 00:24:13.620
Raphael paints a wonderful
picture of the earthly city,

00:24:13.620 --> 00:24:16.380
heavenly city.

00:24:16.380 --> 00:24:22.530
Pope Urban II in 1080 in talking
to the Crusades in Europe

00:24:22.530 --> 00:24:26.580
before they set off
for Jerusalem talks

00:24:26.580 --> 00:24:33.660
to them about taking the earthly
city and the heavenly city.

00:24:33.660 --> 00:24:38.320
The invention of heaven
is a human invention.

00:24:38.320 --> 00:24:50.280
The Hebrews, the Jews didn't in
early accept the idea of a life

00:24:50.280 --> 00:24:56.340
beyond the normal daily
experience of life.

00:24:56.340 --> 00:25:01.110
The center is not
only the position

00:25:01.110 --> 00:25:05.490
of maximum concentration,
it is the position

00:25:05.490 --> 00:25:10.020
of maximum identification.

00:25:10.020 --> 00:25:16.680
It's described in many of
these terms in cosmic terms

00:25:16.680 --> 00:25:20.620
not only as a functional
economic center, but as

00:25:20.620 --> 00:25:24.390
the central place which
distinguishes itself

00:25:24.390 --> 00:25:26.670
from other place.

00:25:26.670 --> 00:25:32.460
In Eliade's terms, there's a
difference between the sacred

00:25:32.460 --> 00:25:34.380
and the profane.

00:25:34.380 --> 00:25:38.190
The profane is the
everyday world.

00:25:38.190 --> 00:25:44.040
Reverse it, our secular world
is not in our terms profane.

00:25:44.040 --> 00:25:48.810
But in archaic times, he argues,
the secular world is profane.

00:25:48.810 --> 00:25:53.130
The religious world,
the only world,

00:25:53.130 --> 00:25:57.510
purposely created through
hierophany of significance.

00:26:03.640 --> 00:26:09.070
Eliade argues that the third
impact on the form of towns

00:26:09.070 --> 00:26:13.210
were rituals,
significant gestures

00:26:13.210 --> 00:26:17.500
to acquire meaning
attributed to them.

00:26:17.500 --> 00:26:22.990
I might not have time to go into
these examples in China, India,

00:26:22.990 --> 00:26:24.670
and Mesoamerica.

00:26:24.670 --> 00:26:30.250
But in the town of
Madurai in Southern India,

00:26:30.250 --> 00:26:34.960
I will show you a slide of the
ritual still practiced today

00:26:34.960 --> 00:26:38.980
of each cycle of
time as time passes.

00:26:38.980 --> 00:26:44.230
According to Eliade, progress
does not seen in terms of time

00:26:44.230 --> 00:26:46.060
by archaic man.

00:26:46.060 --> 00:26:47.350
Time was not linear--

00:26:47.350 --> 00:26:49.070
time was circular.

00:26:49.070 --> 00:26:54.020
There's no notion
about the past.

00:26:54.020 --> 00:26:57.520
The present, the existence
of important things

00:26:57.520 --> 00:27:04.270
is very much in association
with the security

00:27:04.270 --> 00:27:05.740
that you give to everything.

00:27:08.810 --> 00:27:10.880
I'm just conscious
of time so I'm

00:27:10.880 --> 00:27:14.240
going to go through,
skip some of this stuff

00:27:14.240 --> 00:27:18.080
and try to concentrate
on a few of the items.

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:34.330
What I'd like to
do is in relation--

00:27:34.330 --> 00:27:36.940
oh, I didn't tell you
what I handed out to you.

00:27:36.940 --> 00:27:37.690
I'm sorry.

00:27:43.650 --> 00:27:48.970
This is an image of a town.

00:27:48.970 --> 00:27:49.830
Where is it?

00:27:55.750 --> 00:27:58.860
It's a rather famous city.

00:27:58.860 --> 00:28:02.290
It's a classical city.

00:28:02.290 --> 00:28:02.860
It's Athens.

00:28:07.310 --> 00:28:11.030
The image shows Athens
is being built largely

00:28:11.030 --> 00:28:21.470
around an elevated
system of space

00:28:21.470 --> 00:28:26.840
called the Acropolis,
a religious god.

00:28:26.840 --> 00:28:38.180
And its extension to the water
around the town of Pireas,

00:28:38.180 --> 00:28:43.380
the Harbor of Pireas,
depicts the implication

00:28:43.380 --> 00:28:48.300
of building a town whose form
is much more mechanical and much

00:28:48.300 --> 00:28:51.630
more of the kind that we
will talk about next Tuesday.

00:28:51.630 --> 00:28:57.900
We have two forms of the
same system, one dedicated.

00:28:57.900 --> 00:29:06.630
We know Pireas is purely a place
in conjunction with an expanded

00:29:06.630 --> 00:29:09.630
view of the Mediterranean--

00:29:09.630 --> 00:29:14.040
the Acropolis of Athens
plus the monuments of gods

00:29:14.040 --> 00:29:14.925
all over Athens.

00:29:20.010 --> 00:29:24.240
Depicts a consciousness
of what we

00:29:24.240 --> 00:29:29.430
might call the religious gene.

00:29:29.430 --> 00:29:33.870
The greatest gene is a
term taken from archaeology

00:29:33.870 --> 00:29:36.150
relatively recently.

00:29:36.150 --> 00:29:42.120
And based on excavations
in the Mayan world, which

00:29:42.120 --> 00:29:45.075
argues that belonging
to religions

00:29:45.075 --> 00:29:48.270
was a very, very early
phenomenon, largely

00:29:48.270 --> 00:29:51.540
because of the security
the community gave--

00:29:51.540 --> 00:29:56.340
belonging to the same thing
provided fundamental security.

00:29:56.340 --> 00:30:02.290
And the god gene, in a Darwinian
sense, is built into all of us.

00:30:02.290 --> 00:30:06.600
Those of us who
don't believe in god

00:30:06.600 --> 00:30:10.140
are not part of
the Darwinian bet--

00:30:10.140 --> 00:30:15.780
we are creatures of obstinance--

00:30:15.780 --> 00:30:18.240
and since the
Enlightenment have been

00:30:18.240 --> 00:30:22.350
free to criticize
whatever we want to based

00:30:22.350 --> 00:30:25.230
on fact or on mythology.

00:30:25.230 --> 00:30:27.750
I'm going to go
through the components

00:30:27.750 --> 00:30:29.970
of a theory on the second page.

00:30:29.970 --> 00:30:31.090
AUDIENCE: I have question.

00:30:31.090 --> 00:30:32.300
JULIAN BEINART: Yes.

00:30:32.300 --> 00:30:35.280
AUDIENCE: Regarding the
layout of having both Athens

00:30:35.280 --> 00:30:36.715
and Pireas at the same time.

00:30:36.715 --> 00:30:37.590
JULIAN BEINART: Yeah.

00:30:37.590 --> 00:30:42.440
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] social
division between them?

00:30:42.440 --> 00:30:45.480
And if so, what were
the different types

00:30:45.480 --> 00:30:50.750
of social groups, like
division one versus the other?

00:30:50.750 --> 00:30:54.940
JULIAN BEINART: Athens during
the fifth century, and only

00:30:54.940 --> 00:30:59.740
for one century,
experimented with democracy.

00:30:59.740 --> 00:31:03.850
At that time, all citizens
were considered equal,

00:31:03.850 --> 00:31:05.475
except for women or slaves.

00:31:08.500 --> 00:31:12.140
There's a machine in
the museum in Athens

00:31:12.140 --> 00:31:15.580
which is almost like
a machine in which you

00:31:15.580 --> 00:31:19.720
put in your fingerprint and
it registers you for voting.

00:31:22.550 --> 00:31:29.500
So in Democratic Athens,
as Socrates would explain,

00:31:29.500 --> 00:31:34.330
all people were considered
equal in the first notion

00:31:34.330 --> 00:31:36.310
of a crude democracy.

00:31:36.310 --> 00:31:39.460
It didn't last very long.

00:31:39.460 --> 00:31:47.180
Athens is situated in rocky
country, very poor agriculture.

00:31:47.180 --> 00:31:52.780
So it's dependent on other
sources of basic supply

00:31:52.780 --> 00:31:57.610
of food, such as wheat.

00:31:57.610 --> 00:31:59.860
In later years, it
was so desperate

00:31:59.860 --> 00:32:05.470
that it tried to attacked
Sicily, which has always been

00:32:05.470 --> 00:32:09.220
a center of wheat production.

00:32:09.220 --> 00:32:15.160
So Pireas was part of the
extension of Athens for food.

00:32:15.160 --> 00:32:19.120
It was purely a
machine-like enterprise.

00:32:19.120 --> 00:32:24.100
It only had to produce
goods for the service

00:32:24.100 --> 00:32:28.330
of the democratic capital,
which was experimenting

00:32:28.330 --> 00:32:31.270
with all kinds of ways
of life, including

00:32:31.270 --> 00:32:36.940
the purposeful
application of democracy.

00:32:36.940 --> 00:32:41.650
Within Athens, democratic
Athens itself, yes, there

00:32:41.650 --> 00:32:44.350
were areas where
the more powerful

00:32:44.350 --> 00:32:47.350
lived and there were areas
with the less powerful.

00:32:47.350 --> 00:32:50.590
Socrates himself used
to walk through Athens

00:32:50.590 --> 00:32:52.390
on a daily basis.

00:32:52.390 --> 00:32:54.700
It was small enough to do that.

00:32:54.700 --> 00:32:57.490
And he would go through
different neighborhoods,

00:32:57.490 --> 00:32:59.740
according to his
own descriptions.

00:32:59.740 --> 00:33:02.020
Socrates never wrote, of course.

00:33:02.020 --> 00:33:07.320
So it's all told by
Plato and other people.

00:33:07.320 --> 00:33:11.275
But that's the short
answer to a long question.

00:33:14.110 --> 00:33:22.880
The history of Athens is an
